00:08:15.440 --> 00:08:19.720
I don't know if I gave enough
emphasis to the central limit

00:08:19.720 --> 00:08:22.113
theorem last lecture.

00:08:24.750 --> 00:08:32.250
This is a fundamental theorem
from probability theory, which

00:08:32.250 --> 00:08:44.890
says that if you have
independent identically

00:08:44.890 --> 00:08:47.770
distributed random variables.

00:08:54.340 --> 00:08:58.620
That is, every random variable
is independent of the other,

00:08:58.620 --> 00:09:02.050
and they're all of the same
distribution, and if it has a

00:09:02.050 --> 00:09:10.930
finite variance, then the
distribution of an average of

00:09:10.930 --> 00:09:17.090
these variables converges to the
normal distribution as the

00:09:17.090 --> 00:09:21.510
number of elements in the
average is increased.

00:09:21.510 --> 00:09:25.020
In other words, averages are
approximately normally

00:09:25.020 --> 00:09:26.120
distributed.

00:09:26.120 --> 00:09:30.910
The bell-shaped curve works as
well as it does, because so

00:09:30.910 --> 00:09:34.350
many things we observe in
nature are averages.

00:09:34.350 --> 00:09:38.160
So many things that we observe
are the sum of many affects.

00:09:38.160 --> 00:09:40.270
This is what history
is all about.

00:09:40.270 --> 00:09:44.070
Anytime big events occur, it's
probably because a number of

00:09:44.070 --> 00:09:47.470
things chanced to happen
at the same time.

00:09:47.470 --> 00:09:52.480
And that's why probability
Theorists think that we kind

00:09:52.480 --> 00:09:56.450
of know the probability
distribution, and that's this

00:09:56.450 --> 00:10:02.640
bell-shaped curve which I had
on the slide last period.

00:10:02.640 --> 00:10:05.420
The critical thing about the
bell-shaped curve is that the

00:10:05.420 --> 00:10:08.720
tails drop off really fast,
after you get a certain

00:10:08.720 --> 00:10:10.520
distance up on either end.

00:10:10.520 --> 00:10:11.710
They essentially hit zero.

00:10:11.710 --> 00:10:12.750
They never hit zero.

00:10:12.750 --> 00:10:14.860
The probability is never zero.

00:10:14.860 --> 00:10:22.200
Anything can happen with a
normally distributed variable.

00:10:22.200 --> 00:10:29.880
But the normal distribution
does not have fat tails.

00:10:29.880 --> 00:10:33.440
After two or three or four
standard deviations, basically

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:36.190
the probability is zero
that that kind

00:10:36.190 --> 00:10:38.500
of thing will happen.

00:10:38.500 --> 00:10:39.230
That a return --

00:10:39.230 --> 00:10:42.070
if we're applying
it to returns,

00:10:42.070 --> 00:10:46.760
that that would occur.

00:10:46.760 --> 00:10:50.480
So, the problem with the central
limit theorem is that

00:10:50.480 --> 00:10:52.900
it's only as good as
its assumptions.

00:10:52.900 --> 00:10:56.950
And it assumes that the
underlying variables have a

00:10:56.950 --> 00:11:01.140
finite variance, that they
themselves are not so

00:11:01.140 --> 00:11:06.220
fat-tailed that the variance
of them in infinite.

00:11:06.220 --> 00:11:09.850
And in fact, that assumption
might be wrong, because we

00:11:09.850 --> 00:11:15.390
see, especially in finance, we
see big outliers coming from

00:11:15.390 --> 00:11:16.640
time to time.

00:11:19.180 --> 00:11:21.920
And so I present a theory, and
I must say I like the theory.

00:11:21.920 --> 00:11:24.480
The central limit theory is an
important theory, but it's

00:11:24.480 --> 00:11:25.550
also wrong.

00:11:25.550 --> 00:11:29.030
And that's the problem with
financial theory.

00:11:29.030 --> 00:11:33.070
It's not quite as good as the
theory that physicists or

00:11:33.070 --> 00:11:33.950
chemists use.

00:11:33.950 --> 00:11:37.550
It has its limitations.

00:11:37.550 --> 00:11:39.850
Nonetheless, that's what
we have to talk about.

00:11:39.850 --> 00:11:43.665
We have to make do with that
as much as we can.

00:11:48.020 --> 00:11:50.980
I'm almost done with my review
of the last lecture.

00:11:50.980 --> 00:11:54.650
I wanted to just correct
what I said.

00:11:54.650 --> 00:11:57.880
I said that fat-tailed
distributions were discovered

00:11:57.880 --> 00:12:03.540
by Benoit Mandelbrot,
but that's --

00:12:03.540 --> 00:12:05.405
I have to give credit
properly.

00:12:05.405 --> 00:12:08.320
It's actually his teacher,
so I've got this now.

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:23.710
Paul Pierre Levy was a
mathematician who lived from

00:12:23.710 --> 00:12:29.400
1886 to 1971, who really first
developed a theory of

00:12:29.400 --> 00:12:31.570
fat-tailed distribution.

00:12:31.570 --> 00:12:38.760
And he was at the Ecole
Polytechnique in France.

00:12:38.760 --> 00:12:46.890
And his student was Benoit
Mandelbrot, who was one of the

00:12:46.890 --> 00:12:48.690
great mathematicians --

00:12:48.690 --> 00:12:51.260
they're both among the great
mathematicians of the

00:12:51.260 --> 00:12:52.510
twentieth century.

00:12:56.726 --> 00:13:00.630
Our knowledge of fat-tailed
distributions comes down to us

00:13:00.630 --> 00:13:03.030
through word of mouth.

00:13:03.030 --> 00:13:06.570
From Levy, who was Mandelbrot's
teacher, to

00:13:06.570 --> 00:13:09.590
Mandelbrot, to me, and
then to you, I think.

00:13:09.590 --> 00:13:13.780
So, we don't require any printed
word to know this.

00:13:13.780 --> 00:13:16.370
That's the way the history
of thought goes.

00:13:19.450 --> 00:13:23.270
There's an old joke about
the normal distribution.

00:13:23.270 --> 00:13:25.180
The joke goes as follows.

00:13:25.180 --> 00:13:31.790
The mathematicians think that
the normal distribution is

00:13:31.790 --> 00:13:35.390
ubiquitous in nature, because
applied workers have

00:13:35.390 --> 00:13:39.140
discovered that everything
is normally distributed.

00:13:39.140 --> 00:13:43.140
But applied workers think that
the normal distribution is

00:13:43.140 --> 00:13:46.620
ubiquitous in nature, because
mathematicians have proved

00:13:46.620 --> 00:13:49.040
that it's ubiquitous
in nature.

00:13:49.040 --> 00:13:53.000
In fact, it's sort of
ubiquitous, but it sort of

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:53.880
surprises you.

00:13:53.880 --> 00:13:54.530
And that's one of the

00:13:54.530 --> 00:13:58.080
fundamental lessons in finance.

00:13:58.080 --> 00:14:01.040
The fundamental lesson in
finance is that you might go

00:14:01.040 --> 00:14:04.900
through years observing some
random return, or some random

00:14:04.900 --> 00:14:08.040
variable in finance, and you
kind of think you know how it

00:14:08.040 --> 00:14:10.890
behaves, and you've learned
some confidence.

00:14:10.890 --> 00:14:13.830
There will come a day when
it defies all of your

00:14:13.830 --> 00:14:17.660
expectations, and that's what
fat-tails are all about.

